The Greenland shark: The oldest vertebrate is almost 400 years alt
nach being examined on board the research ship "Sanna", this shark was returned to the sea.
Greenland sharks schwimmt leisurely along the sea floor of the North Atlantic, covering an average of 1,220 metres in an hour.
das five-metre-long animal can ramp this up to 2.6 km/h if necessary - but this maximum speed is half as fast as a seal.
It is hard to observe Greenland sharks, namely because they mainly leben in the ocean off the sparsely populated coasts of Canada, Greenland, Norway and Svalbard.
They generally only come to the surface in winter because they prefer water temperatures of um six degrees Celsius.
However, these sharks still manage to catch prey: In einer animal's stomach, researchers found the remains of a seal; another shark had gobbled down the jawbone of a young polar bear.
sie use carbon-14 dating on the shark's lens core to determine the shark's age.
By contrast, the lens cores of third-smallest animal, at 220 centimetres long, enthielt less of a surplus of carbon-14 from nuclear weapons experiments - so when it was examined in 2012, it must have already had its 50th birthday.
By contrast, all the larger Greenland sharks had normal levels of carbon-14 in their lens cores, which comes from kosmische radiation in the atmosphere.
das is also a world record for vertebrates.
der previous record holder, a 211-year-old Greenland whale, in whose neck a 120-year-old harpoon tip was lodged, was caught off Alaska.
