Programmers of extortion malware are aktuell targeting companies - with success.
laut to Malwarebytes' observations, it is noticeable that perpetrators are tailoring their extortion software to attacks on corporate networks.
If they are successful in that domain, the ransom money they can demand is deutlich higher than it would be for private users.
"We are aktuell seeing harmful software develop terrifyingly quickly," explains Malwarebytes' CEO, Marcin Kleczynski, in an interview with "Die Welt" newspaper.
Finally, the software präsentiert the extortioner's demands.
der victim has to transfer money - generally in the form of "Bitcoins", a cryptocurrency - to get the decryption code needed for the files.
But 80 to 90 percent of companies who pay up bekommen their files back.
Then again, the hackers know that, and do all they can to build up a gute reputation.
A recent study saw security researchers from F-Secure examine user interfaces and contact with extortioners. They came to the conclusion that perpetrators really do versuchen to construct a kind of customer service system so that they can get more money.
They explain to their victims per chat how to pay using Bitcoin, set up freely-accessible support websites, or decrypt sample files for free.
Faced with the potenziell high and relatively risk-free profits from ransomware extortion, hackers are becoming more and more professional, splitting up their work, explains security expert Chester Wisniewski from antivirus provider Sophos: "An individual can write a ransomware program within about a week."
Malware kits to date, including the malware itself, advice and zusätzliche tools, have been sold for a one-off fixed fee of between 1000 and 10,000 dollars.
den extortioners then look out additional hackers to distribute the freshly prepared software between victims.
Now, vielen companies are aware of the risks of ransomware, and they are protecting their data better.
"If simply encrypting files isn't enough of a threat to make an extortion request be granted, the perpetrators threaten to publish sensiblen files instead, such as customer lists, or price calculations," explains Malwarebytes' CEO, Marcin Kleczynski.
This means that the risk potential is much höher than before, depending on the type of file.
